replies.comment info:
@Bella 
I dont think the unemployment rate has ‘barely budged’
It’s clearly gone up and down quite a lot. Even after april it has gone down to be closer to how it was in january

@Katie Thank you for sharing these great insights. You picked up a few great noticings here: that layoffs were more temporary during the initial lockdown and that unemployment is still higher in September than at pre-pandemic times (January).

Why would companies frame layoffs as temporary in April? What happened share of temporary vs. permanent layoffs as we approached September? What may be behind this trend?

Would love to hear further thoughts.

@Tucker Thank you for sharing! I especially appreciate your wondering: "I wonder why a lot of the people that had jobs were temporary laid off. And people are waiting to see if they get there job back."

One further thought: Compare the share of layoffs that are temporary vs permanent in January. Now, compare these shares in September. How does this inform your wondering?

Let me know what you think!

@jane.aose Great noticing here: "starts small and then a huge bulge in the graph and never goes back to the slim amount that it started at." You attribute these changes to the pandemic and ensuing recovery, although job levels never quite come back to their pre-pandemic levels. I think you're spot on.

I'm also a fan of your wondering: "Is this because of the pandemic, are there job shortages or is it because people are unable to work due to this virus?"

Take a look at the "Other" category. This describes folks who can't work due to transportation issues, needing to care for their family, susceptibility to the virus, and other issues. How does this part of the graph inform your wondering?

@Mrs Ellis SS class Great noticings and wonderings. Thank you for sharing with all of us.

I particularly like this wondering: "I wonder if the people that are temporarily laid off will be able to go back to work or if their businesses will permanently close."

Let's dig deeper into that question. Take a look at the share of unemployment that was temporary vs. permanent in January. Compare these shares (temporary and permanent) in April. Finally, compare these shares in September. What trends do you notice? How might this inform your question? Would love to hear your thoughts!

@Sam This is an extremely interesting wondering. Let's expand on that with some further questions:

As Covid-19 hits a resurgence, what kind of shift do we expect to see in the graph's overall width? What kind of shift do we expect to see in the share of unemployment that is temporary vs. permanent? Will there be a shift at all? 

Would love to hear your thoughts.

@anisa rodriguez Great thoughts! Thank you for sharing. 

Let me clarify the categories a bit, in terms of "wanting" a job. The government's definition of "unemployment" only counts those who are temporarily laid off or who have looked for work in the past four weeks. People who haven’t actively sought work in the last four weeks, even if they want jobs, are considered out of the labor force and are not counted. So, both groups tend to still "want" jobs, which is why both are shown here.

I love this wondering: "I wonder if the graph would be a lot different if there wasn't the ongoing pandemic among society." What made you believe the pandemic affected the shape of this graph? What attributes (time, width, height, etc.) made you believe the pandemic was a cause of unemployment trends?

@Chase Thank you for sharing, and I love your noticings about the rate of job loss over time.

Let's push a little further: How does the unemployment amount in September compare to April? How does it compare to January? What does this say about the economic recovery overall?

Let me know what you think!

@Quiomalis Great noticing! You do a great job capturing the multiple variables at play here - unemployment, time, and the start of the pandemic.

You have a great noticing of unemployment decreasing since April, which was near the start of the pandemic (at least, in the U.S.). 

One question to go further: in September, are unemployment levels larger or smaller than they were back in January? What does this say about the recovery relative to a more "normal" pre-pandemic time (back in January)?
